 of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Poultney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Pountney  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Pountney","meanings":["English: locative name from Poultney (Leics), which is recorded as  <i>Pontenei</i> in 1086 and  <i>Pulteney</i> in 1220. The place-name derives from an Old English personal name * <i>Pulta</i> (genitive * <i>Pultan</i>) + Old English  <i>ēg</i> ‘island, piece of dry ground in a fen’."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Japanese: written 井伊 ‘well’ and ‘that’, the name one of Japan's great daimyō families, originally based in Tōtōmi (now part of Shizuoka prefecture), later in Kōzuke (now Gunma prefecture) and Ōmi (now Shiga prefecture). Other variants of the name substitute either character with similar sounding characters such as 飯 ‘cooked rice’, 居 ‘residence’, and so forth. It was formerly Romanized as <b>Iyi</b>. — Note: In the population figure published by the US Census Bureau, the Roman number <i>II</i> (meaning ‘the second’, i.e. ‘the younger’ of the two bearers of the name) is apparently also counted as a surname <i>Ii</i>.","History: Ii Naomasa (1561–1602) was awarded lands in Kōzuke and Ōmi for his service in the civil wars that won the shōgunate (military dictatorship) for Tokugawa Ieyasu. His family built the beautiful castle of Hikone, which still stands. His descendant Ii Naosuke (1815–1860) ruled Japan for two years as Tairō (Great Elder) and played a major part in signing treaties that opened Japan to foreign trade at the end of the Tokugawa Shōgunate. He was assassinated by adherents of the anti-foreign party."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Nigel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the medieval name <i>Nigellus</i>, a Latinized version (ostensibly representing a diminutive of Latin <i>niger</i> ‘black’) of the vernacular <i>Ni(h)el</i>, i.e.   Neil .  Although it is frequently found in medieval records, this form was probably not used in everyday life before its revival by antiquarians such as  Sir Walter  Scott in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Nigel de Poultney II was born about 1236, in Misterton, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Hugo de Poultney, was 28 and his mother, Mrs. Hugo De Poultney, was 24. He married Mrs. Nigel De Poultney about 1261, in Misterton, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1236–":"umbes 1236–Surnud","1236–Male":"1236–Surnud","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1262–Male":"1262–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1214–Female":"1214–Surnud","ABT 1261":"umbes 1261","Abt 1262":"umbes 1262","1214":"1214","1236":"1236","1210":"1210","ABT 1235":"umbes 1235","Abt 1236":"umbes 1236","1262":"1262","1240":"1240","Misterton, Leicestershire, England":"Misterton, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Misterton, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Misterton, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1236–":"noin 1236–Kuollut","1236–Male":"1236–Kuollut","1240–Female":"1240–Kuollut","1262–Male":"1262–Kuollut","1210–Male":"1210–Kuollut","1214–Female